<br>
-Pulling has aggro and if a monk pulls then you have to try extra hard to regain aggro.<br>
<br>
-The delta difference between dps seems to have an impact.  I had no haste/no shaman buffs and a monk was doing ~75dps + 100pts proc and I was doing ~50dps + taunting blow proc(not maxed dex) and I had a very difficult time tuanting off him when he was not kicking.  Then I had shaman haste/buffs and he was doing 100dps + 100pts proc and I was doing 75dps with the proc and I had a much easier time taunting... as long as he did not kick.<br>
<br>
-If you want to feel like a gimp, have a monk kick when your playing main tank.<br>
<br>
-the best order of debuffing a mob is: land tash after a tick, land slow after tash, land ch after slow and snare after slow.  Rarely will a mob aggro on those casters.<br>
<br>
-Sit aggro is huge and casters know it and if you pull, sit to direct the mob to you.<br>
<br>
-I have seen casters nuke once and get mad aggro.  This may be a random element.<br>
<br>
-Mobs may have a flip flop element to aggro which causes the mob to stay glued to a partular pc.  The apparent weakness of a pc may be directly related to their hit points.... low level aggro. (note the MAY) &lt;flip flop is defined as: if 100 aggro more then stay on that PC OR if delta aggro is &gt; 1000 stay on that pc &gt;<br>
<br>
-casting has some aggro associated with it.  A mage MGB rod on a pull will generate aggro... and a lot of it.  This does not, however, explain abitration or group heals.<br>
<br>
PS I did ask that fellow from Michigan &quot;how does aggro work&quot; at the Seattle FF and he promptly ignored the comment. =D <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
