I don't really buy this.  How many times have you seen mobs pong back and forth and back and forth to the point of nearly several times a second.  I find it hard to believe that this would happen on both xp groups AND small groups down to and including partnering (like in the bst/war partner example used).<br>
<br>
What I propose is kinda a combo of that and what Brutul said and the above formula. <br>
<br>
People have always worked (as far as I've read) on the assumption that 'on top of the hate list by a small amount' meant that your hate was being raised.  Perhaps it is not the taunter's hate that is being raised, but the gap between you and the #2 person being widened... in effect lowering <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>their</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> hate.  I realize that is splitting hairs, but if you think about it, it does change things.<br>
<br>
example (first 5 hate slots):<br>
<br>
pre warrior taunt..<br>
<br>
Rogue01hate:1345<br>
WarriorMThate:1320<br>
Ranger07hate:1300<br>
Cleric03hate:1100<br>
Cleric04hate:1050<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>after taunt</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
WarriorMThate:1330 (extra 10 built by normal dps hate accumulation)<br>
Rogue01hate:1280<br>
Ranger07hate:1250<br>
Cleric03hate:1050<br>
Cleric04hate:1000<br>
<br>
<br>
Keep in mind this theory is cohesive with the thinking that mashing the taunt button after you are at the top of the hate list will produce nothing.  It also, and perhaps more importantly, works with the idea that taunt does <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>not</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> accrue aggro.  As you will just reset the gap between #1 and #2 on the hate list.  If anything, pressing taunt in this scenario could prove detrimental.  <br>
This seems to make the most sense in my head, but of course... I could just be really tired.<br>
