<br>
- Taunt success rate is modified by how much hate you presently have on the target compared to everyone else. <br>
<br>
-Taunting a guy you're presently attacking succeeds much more often than one you're not attacking, but others are. <br>
<br>
-Taunting a mob that you're not attacking, and noone else, succeeds often as well. <br>
<br>
-Taunt almost always fails if you are not attacking the mob but only using taunt, and others are using spells to generate aggro, as well as taunting and meleeing. Try it. <br>
<br>
-I believe mez is a low enough aggro that it allows warriors taunt to succeed often.<br>
<br>
-Attempting to taunt a mob that someone else has lots of aggro on and you don't, fails often as well. (think moving to a  CC'd mob at 60 health being CC'd by a paladin after the first target is dead)<br>
<br>
-Taunt does add a random amount on top of the list.<br>
<br>
4: AE taunt is an 100% sucess rate AoE verstion of taunt. It ALWAYS succeeds, no matter what. However, low health aggro will push the person back on top of the hate list almost instantly. (They turn to me, then turn back)<br>
<br>
I've AE taunted 10-15 mobs on me many times. Sometimes as soon as I get my first spot heal all those mobs then jump the caster/healer. Other times, Those mobs stick to me for a good 30 seconds until the AE'ing wizards pull aggro off.<br>
<br>
<br>
To sum up:<br>
<br>
Taunt is not some set chance of getting to the top of list+1, it is top of list +an amount determined by taunt skill and luck. Taunt success rate is determined by several factors, including how much hate you presently have on the target compared to others, how much hate you are presently adding to the target (mob's usually going to ignore you just sitting there and taunting it if some melee's pounding the crap out of it), whether you are in PoP or not, and your skill in taunt.<br>
